segments.text: So anyway, then when we got our health center built, a big part of my practice was the zoo.
I'd go there every day for two or three or four hours, whatever necessitated.
And then still I had a large animal practice, equine practice.

And then I recommended that they get a full-time veterinarian at the zoo, and I did not want it because I had a pretty good equine practice, and I've got a couple of farms, and I kind of like to do different things.

so then they hired a couple of full-time and one of them so they didn't do they didn't get they did yeah yeah and i do work i go there once a while when they somebody's out of town dr fletcher's there now he's in there all the people that i know didn't zoo worker in there and uh so present time and we have tom mitch and aazv
About the time I started zoo work, the American Association of Zoo Veterinarians was just started.
And we had no literature, we had no books, we had no normals.
I think the first meeting I went to was... Michigan State.
I guess it was...
It was the only one they had.
Yeah, I guess that was back about 19... had to be about 1960.
No, about 60, 61, 62.
It was in the early 60s when they had a few meetings.
Yeah, and there were only, I think there were 15.
I went to Michigan State, when Tom and I went, and I started going to them, we went to Michigan State, the Kellogg Center.
There was 15 or 18 veterinarians there, and they met once a year, and we still had very little

information knowledge books literature so then it now it is i go every year went to hawaii and went to australia last year and the avian society a avian association met with a zoo vendor in hawaii year before last and now there's international organizations there are thousands of members and we have
books that we have some gentlemen that are really specialists at it, Dr. Murray Fowler in Davis, California, and some other people.
And we have a lot of things, Tom.
Really, a lot of information.
In fact, I tell people that in that field, and I think just what Stubby's saying, that the last about probably five to six or seven years,
I've been on the greatest learning curve of my career in these species because the information's being disseminated and published and flowing.
And I've learned more medical, gained more medical knowledge in those species in the last five or six years than the other 20 years put together.
You know, because we were just down here stumbling along, trying to do the best we could.
And nobody to talk to or share information.
Colleges have some people.
They had one man several years ago, a very good friend of mine, died.
I was a pulper.
Dr. Dean Brown was the only exotic teacher at A&M.
They only had one course.
Now they have a couple of men, and they're going to have to expand.
They're going to have to expand.
The demand I want to get into, I want to bring this up because it is important.
I went to Australia the year before last to wildlife it.
And there are only two of us in the United States that are exotic veterinarians, wildlife.
Over there, for example, in Texas now, exotic medicine, there's ranches.
I have ranches from five acres to thousands of acres.
They have eight-foot fences around them.
I have an article written on that.
You've got them fenced in now.
When their population increases, if you don't take care of them, feed them, supplement them, get rid of the surplus, you create a monster.
And I can tell you many things about this.
Anyway, it's created a new business in Texas, exotic medicine, because now we have, you can come to Texas and hunt or shoot any kind of a trophy that's in Africa.
There's more black buck antelope and axis deer in Texas than there is in Asia where they originated.
I mean, by thousands.
Is that right?
That's interesting.
I know we've got some around College Station.
I had a friend, a client, Mr. Liu from Taiwan that raised axis.
We shipped three loads.
by Flying Tiger Airlines to Taiwan.
Now he has a ranch in Taiwan.
And when I was in Australia, we stayed on a game farm for two nights.
They get more for the horns that are cut off in the velvet that the Taiwanese and some of the people think are an aphrodisiac and make you live forever.
They get more for that and they do the meat.
Now here in Texas, the meat, some of it, but there's too many hunters in Texas.
The thing in Texas that it's really doing is trophy hunting, the big trophy heads of all these axes, greater kudu, lesser kudu, sable antelope, you name it.
It's created a complete new thing, and it's growing ostriches right now real hot.
They were getting $800 for a little three- or four-month-old ostrich.
Now, a gentleman told me the other day they're getting $3,000 to $4,000, and he bought a pair of ostrich for $82,000.
five-year-old breeding stock.
He has an incubator he paid $70,000.
And they all think they're going to get rich, but the very few of them are going to make any money.
You may not have heard of him, but Fred Thornberry, who's an A&M in poker science, he's been getting a lot of this exotic bird inquiry.
Boy, he says, when they come to me with ostriches now, I tell them, you know,
Stay out of it.
You're going to lose your shirt.
And he said, they'll do it anyway.
They'll do it anyway.
You can't tell.
They have the money and the ostrich skin boots and the feathers and something unique.
People have money.
They're going to do something with it.
I'm going to California next month to visit Murray Fowler.
I'll talk to A&M.
And they're limited.
I'm limited.
as to the whole ostrich picture, and I know more than most people.
I have more experience with them.
But we have, you know, when each phase of each one specific individual animal all of a sudden gets popular, then everybody knows a thing about it, and there's one alcohol.
It concentrates the problems, too.
You know, some guy can have a
one or two ostriches out here, or a few of them, and he's raised them, and he doesn't have any problem.
But when you start getting 40 or 50 of them, you start having overcrowding, and your nutritional problems, and disease control.
Parasite problems.
Yeah, parasite problems, and then it just accentuates.
I have a little article I wrote about 12 years ago.
When I was doing the zoo work, and I started going to ranches, and with the ant ranches in the 70s, everybody was putting an eight-foot fence around them.
50 or 100 or 20 or whatever.
And all of a sudden, they start like this.
And I wrote a little article.
I always used to go talk to them.
I'd talk to them at Chamber of Commerce and there and places they'd get me to come up and talk to them.
And I finally have a little article that has an outline.
When you get older population, you're going to get reproduction.
You get malnutrition.
You get parasitism.
You get crowding, male-female imbalance.
You get all these things occur.
Man creates them and puts them in an eight-foot fence.
If the weather, normally they migrate if they run out of fruit on that place.
When you put them in an eight-foot fence, they can't migrate.
And I've been on ranches that some supposedly intelligent good people had, and they wouldn't feed them.
You'd go out and be carcass land.
Now, I wanted to.
I've reported some of them to Humane Society.
Some of the people were afraid of them.
They had a lot of clout.
But anyway, you can imagine what you get.
And it's still going on, and it's...
It's going to continue to go on, but mainly in Texas, in my opinion, at the present time, the trophy heads are worth more than anything.
But ostriches are hot now, llamas are hot, and it's going to go from animal to animal.
Llamas are a big thing.
I used to refer llamas.
I used to have a client at Fort Terrace Ranch in the other side of Junction, a real fine man, Mr. Noel, had just a play thing.
He just had a few because of friends, and he liked them.
You'd get ostriches, everything just running around.
They were all gentle.
You could feed them.
A male ostrich, by the way, besides a casserine, is probably the most dangerous.
They have a middle toe about that long.
And with a male ostrich, I have pictures of dents in pickup trucks.
A male ostrich in mating season will attack a bulldozer or an airplane.
He has no fear of anything.
We've had to decoy him to get through fences.
They can jump up and hit you.
They can open you up.
I've got pictures of them.
They're very dangerous.
Most people don't realize it.
Oh, they're dangerous.
That's the reason I'm glad to refer those to stuff.
All your large breeds of birds at the zoo, I learned this over Mr. Chisholm when I first went.
Big pelicans and cranes that have long beaks.
Like Tom said, the animal that's raised in captivity has no fear of man.
He is the most dangerous.
All for different reasons.
And you walk in one of their pens and they'll walk up to you.
And if they don't like it, before they hit you in the eye.
So you never get into it and never let them get too close to you.
So that's a true statement there.
But anyway, so, you know, let's see.
I was kind of putting an outline in front of it.
Oh, that's interesting, too.
That's good information.
But it's a changing picture.
And cage birds, like Tom said, are just,
And exotic animals are just going crazy in this state.
We have a climate where a lot of them do well and we have a lot of people with small ranches and farms that get interested and have a little extra money.
So when did you, when did you essentially step out of the zoo work?
Well I, I, oh let's see, 78 to 80 something, about nine years ago.
And then they got another veterinarian and he quit and I went back and worked with him on a contract part-time basis.
And now they call it a swab and he's out of town.
I like ranch exotic work.
I really like it.
It's challenging.
It's every ranch is different.
It's a different environment.
You have partners, associates?
No, I'm by myself.
Dr. James and I sold that place.
Everybody's scattered like a bunch of quail.
You're not thinking about bringing anybody else in with you?
No, I want to keep it simple.
I want to keep it simple and do what I can do.

You know, you get a little older, you get cranky, and you get more particular, and you kind of, I know what I know, and I know my limitations, and I'll refer somebody else to something I can do, I think I can do justice to.
I'll do it.
If not, I'll refer somebody else.
Do you have any working associations at A&M, at the college or anything, or do you have much involvement with them at all?
Not right now.

We were talking about having some practitioners that are knowledgeable and experienced come up and have some little group seminars, kind of like Tom was doing, except he was doing it for the students and the other practitioners.
But they're going to have to do it because unless they get a couple of knowledgeable professors out there that are more versatile.
Well, and the problem is we've recommended for the last several years that they get a clinician.
full-time clinician, at least in Cagesburg Medicine or in Cagesburg Medicine and other exotics.
And the problem in talking with Dr. Samuelson is the fact that the college can get money for a piece of equipment easier than they can for a new staff position.
And so their budget limitations have really thwarted that.
They want to do that, but they've just not been able to do that.
The gentleman he talked about is Cagesburg, and they have Dr. Jensen, a young veterinarian who I talked to at the state meeting a while
But they need it.
They have to use him in everything.
He can't just dedicate himself to exotics and that kind of thing.
I called up there last week and talked to Dr. Julep, who's in charge of postgraduate seminars.
He's a personal friend of mine.
And he said, they're hard to catch, and I want to go up and visit with them for a day.
And they're just snowed.
Yeah.
Well, you know, that same area, the interest is really there.

You know, Walter can tell you that we, I think it was, I don't know, four or five years ago, we held the first Caged Bird seminar, continuing education seminar for practitioners, and I was on the program, and we brought, let's see, I think we brought Susan Club in from Florida, and Dr. Fred Seufer from
from Houston.
Yeah, you need to talk to Fred.
And we put on the first avian seminar at A&M, and it was the best attended seminar that they'd ever put on up there.
And still continues to be.
Each year they have an avian seminar, and Walter said it still continues to be the best attended seminar he puts on.
So the interest is really there from the practitioners.
Many of them are only going to see
maybe a few of these animals, but they want some knowledge when they do get confronted with it.
I have young veterinarians, and I'm sure Tom does too, that call me, and I'm charging them consultations because I don't want to keep giving out my dosages that it took me 20 years to learn.
And they don't know anything.
They're in a small town.
They're doing a mixed practice because they have to.
And somebody has a llama.
Somebody has an ostrich.
Somebody has this giraffe here last week.
And they call.
And a lot of them have been calling me because I'm one of the few that used to go and stay at ranches on general exotics.
And I don't know it all, but I learned a lot.
And so I try to help them and give them at least something to do.
But that's why Tom says it.
The ostrich seminar, they had a great crowd up there last month.
They had a llama seminar.
Dr. Murray Fowle from Davis, California,
is probably the most knowledgeable general exotic man in the world.
One of them.
And then they're going to have more of them, I'm sure.
They need them.
They have to.
The veterinarians are just groping for knowledge.
And they have to get it or refer to somebody else.
But we should become more specialized than we're going to.
That's good.
That's a good thing.
That's been fascinating.
Let's shift to another area of pioneering veterinary medicine.
Yeah, the real pioneer.
The real pioneer.

In other words, could you tell me a little bit, tell us about how you got into the business and your background and your recollections of entering into the profession, your problems and measures and so forth.
Well, I was born here in San Antonio.
Okay.
And what is your full name?
Norma Anelna Betts.
My husband's name is Brockley, B-R-A-U-C-H-L-E.
So I have a nice alias I can hide.
Well, I kind of feel like this.
I lose my identity completely.
Somebody wants to come to town that I knew 30 years ago, they'd never find me.
I didn't know there was a legal reason for doing that.
No, I do it where I work.
I'm in the elder beds of Brockley.
I think many of the married gals do that.
My daddy busted his butt putting me through school.
Retain their maiden name as their professional name.
Excuse me, go ahead.
No, I was born here.
Oh, I decided when I was about seven I wanted to be a veterinarian.
Did you really?
Yeah, my dad said, well, you know, the sky's the limit.
There was nothing that he ever told me that I couldn't accomplish.
I grew up thinking the world was my oyster.
I'm serious.
My daddy never told me, you can't do this or you can't do that.
You've got to have that attitude to a certain degree.
Too many obstacles.
I graduated from Burbank High School.
I tried to get into A&M, and of course they didn't want me.
When was that?
This was back in graduating from Burbank in 43.
I was 16 years old.
And we had just gone through a short period over there where they had a few women come to school.
Oh, the summer is all they take.
Yeah, because I went over and talked to Dr. Turk on many occasions.
You don't know him.
He was long before you.
Dr. Turk and Dr. Robinson tried.
Yeah, they did try.
They did try.
Because there were a few who were there full-time in the late 30s because of the depression, local faculty-wise.
Yeah, faculty-wise and offspring, but that was all, and certainly not in the area of medicine.
No, that's right.
I mean, that's no place for a female.
That was one of the old eyes.
So my dad wrote the commission of education here, who was at that time Leo Edwards.
He wrote him back that they didn't send women out of state schools.
They'd send black out of state schools, but not a woman.
That made my daddy upset.
So I applied to Auburn.
It was either Auburn or Colorado State.
There weren't that many veterinary schools then.
And those that did have vet schools certainly didn't want to accept a student from a state that had a veterinary school of their own.
But you really had a double problem.
I can see that.
That's right.
Went to Auburn, applied for, well, did my pre-vet work there.
About a year or two later, my family moved there.
That way, I was a resident.
And got in vet school.
See, I'm on through.
We were back on the quarter system then.
Took us four years, three months, and 11 days straight through.
It's tough.
It's during the war.
Learned a lot.
So your family really put a lot into it for you with that degree.
And then you got your degree and you came back to Texas right away.
Came back, yeah.
The same time.
That was home.
My grandparents were here.
So the summer before I graduated, old Dr. Wharton got me a job with Gene Ingram, who I'm sure you've met in the optosis.
at a clinic there on Broadway.
Oh, I remember, yeah.
I was trying to think of his name.
Howard.
And Dr. Barton kind of took me under his wing.
Be careful.
You better be careful.
I never had any problem with him.
I knew him when I was in high school.
He used to come out to Burbank and talk to the class.
You weren't one of the seven wives?
No.
His seventh wife or his fifth wife shot him in the face.
Oh, man, I can...
Put a hole through his head you could throw your hat through.
Shot him three times, once in the front, once in the back, and once in the side as he turned.
And then shot his ex, one of the other ex-wives ran to the bathroom and she emptied a gun in the bathroom door.
Well, he was visiting one of his ex-wives and this other one of his ex-wives...
Early days of the old west.
Hey, you know, all I can say is he did marry him.
Ingram now is, are you in a partnership?
No, no, no, no.
I just worked for him the summer before I graduated.
That was all.
And then when I graduated, I came back.
Dr. Wharton got me a job down at Swift's with Dr. Fisher.
who is now retired and is in .
Is that where he is?
The wife is a physician.
She's a health director down there.
Well, I'll be down there.
And I just decided I really wanted all those darn single trees on the floor and those tubs all day long.
And I was, shoo, I couldn't take it.
And you were inspecting?
Yeah, livers, gallbladders.
A real glamorous job.
That's right.
Oh, hey, you know, at least they equipped you.
I mean, you could get the chain gloves, you know, and stuff like that.
So I went back and graduated.
There was a guy in Georgia who wanted me to come to work for him, so I went and took the state board in Atlanta.
I was the first woman to make the state board there.
It was big, plastered all over the newspaper.
Is that right?
She was the only girl in our...
When I started the school, there were 50 of us in a pre-vet class.
Like I said, four years, three months, and 11 days later, two of us of that 50 graduated together.
The rest of them flunked out or went into the military.
And out of the 27 in our class, 25 were veterans or add-ons.
Only from the Okefenokee Swamp in Georgia.
And I finished together.
Were there other women in that group?
Had there been other women through the program before at Auburn?
Two.
Is that right?
Lucille Demerling and Marie Hall-Alberger, who is quite a mycologist.
I think she did a master's when she was here.
Pardon me.
She went to work for Auburn.
She was faculty.
She was there when I went back for the last reunion.
Came back here, went in small animal practice.
Are you going in on your own?
No, I went with Bob Sturdivant, went to the Aftosa thing.
You remember Bob Sturdivant?
He's in that because he did zoo work.
Everybody that I could find did zoo work.
is in there about the time they did it.
It might help you.
Bob went to a post-problem foot and mouth in Mexico.
And David Sprinkle, who was a small animal veterinarian and lived out here on what was then almost Luke Road, had a clinic and a kennel just down the road from Leo Holbrook.
And I took over the clinic in Alma Heights.
David decided he's going to go back into service and that left me.
And it wasn't really very lucrative.
Sturdivant hadn't been a very frugal businessman.
That's saying it nicely.
Yes, that's very nice.
We can all have comments.
His creditors came and
got his x-ray machine first, and came and got some of his other equipment.
Were you leasing, or what was your situation right now?
Well, I was paying the rent on the place, and then splitting the take with this guy who's in Mexico.
And finally, he said, hey, man, ain't nothing here anymore to practice with, you know?
Bob was known as, I think, probably
The best term, kindest term is a maverick.
He was a wheeler and dealer outside of veterinary medicine.
Got him in trouble all the time.
I saw him one time over at Dale's gun shop and he was buying some, oh he went in there and bought a whole bunch of ammunition and a bunch of clay pigeons, you know.
And a friend of mine was with me in bed there, and he said, well, so-and-so, he owes me, I don't know, $300 or $400 for this and that.
He didn't care.
He'd borrow stuff from everybody in town, and then they'd pay back drugs and everything else.
He was a nice fellow, just nice.
But I mean, he just, he was astute.
So your business is disappearing.
An astute.
Yes.
Your business is physically disappearing.
Yeah.
The equipment was just about to cut.
And about that time,
Bob and I decided to get married, and we leased a sprinkles place out here on Almost Loop Road, which later became Lawndale, and had a kennel there, so I had a clinic there.
And that was for a long time.
Your husband's not a veteran.
No, he's an Aggie, though.
He taught in the veteran's school I taught in.
That's what I was going to say.
He taught now in the veteran's training program.
And they needed another slot.
And you and I, I think, were out there at the same time.
Because I was out in Martinez.
Oh, were you there?
Yeah, I was at Martinez.
And you were?
I was at Charlotte.
Yeah.
And Harold was in Poteet.
Poteet.
And we rotated.
It was the Atascosa County Vocational School.
And it was Veterans Training Program.
Ranch Boys.
Instead of going to college, they got
I went to school a couple of days a week.
Yeah, I went to school a couple of days a week.
And talking about diseases and genetics, no physical treatment or anything.
I didn't compromise.
You did like I did.
I just kind of got to look at it and generalize.
Yeah, I mean, as far as compromising or prostituting my profession, I don't think I can be accused of doing that.
Of course, when I came back to take the state board, Dr. Robinson got Ed Hornicle to get me some old quizzes.
That's...
Okay, let me ask you about the state board.
When you came back to take the state board, was that a problem at all?
No, I don't think it was a problem, was it?
Had other women finished taking the state board?
Were there other women practitioners in Texas at the time?
Or do you know anything specific about it?
Yeah, old Campbell was in Dallas with Dr. MacLeod.
Did it even occur to you that you were doing something different by coming back to practice?
Oh, I had no problem knowing that it was something different.
The members of my class made that perfectly clear.
Were you the only girl in the class in law school?
Well, see, when we took, I was at A&M, I just graduated, and she was the only girl, of course, we had the only girl students at A&M at the time.
I was the only one up there taking the state board.
How were you received locally by your colleagues here?
Well, there were three who really went to bat for me.
Dr. Ray, who happened to be on the board at that time, Al Nagel, who is still living, and Walt Lawrence, who is not living.
Harry Flaticle said, will you come out?
Yeah, you come to work for me.
You want me to clean cages?
I said, really?
I've done enough of that.
Thank you.
If I'm going to clean cages, I'm going to do it for myself.
And so we started the clinic out here, just over the hill from Leo Holbrook.
What was the name of your clinic?
Was it Broadway?
No, I don't know.
Was it Leo Holbrooks?
No, Holbrooks was Broadway.
That was Broadway.
Airport.
Airport, that's right.
Why am I saying that?
Heck, it's still on my checks.
Yeah, that's right.
Airport.
Airport.
And you and your husband were in the business together?
No, he was with the Atascosa County Vocational School.
He's a teacher.
He's a counselor.
Yeah, I know that.
I know he's not a... Yeah, he's not right in there.
But he's not a business associate either in that sense.
Back then and maybe still now, I'm not sure.
You've got to be a veterinarian to be part of the practice.
I didn't know if you could have a business associate.
I've never even thought of having a business associate.
It's been illegal up until recently.
I don't know anybody that is.
This was back when Gleason.
Before Dr. Gleason?
Well, before I graduated from college, old Dr. Gleason and Dr. Ray.
Dr. Ray and, oh, who was the one on San Pedro?
Who was the one down on San Pedro?
I want to, Burby.
Burby.
Would go out and do TB testing and stuff on cattle.
And somebody called and phoned, well, I'll do it for 50 cents a head.
and they'll call somebody else, well, Dr. So-and-so says he'll do it for 50 cents, well, I'll do it for 40.
I mean, you talk about cutthroat.
Well, it's come full circle.
It's right back where it used to be.
This is just exactly what I was going to say.
How long it took us to clean up, if you would, the telephone book.
We talked about that this morning.
And Judas Priest, look at it now.
It's like a bunch of lawyers.
It's worse than it was before.
I mean, if that's what veterinary medicine is all about, that's fine.
It's not for me.
Now, when you started in your clinic, are you doing almost exclusively small animal at this time?
Yes.
Are you doing any large animal practice?
Well, a little bit.
My husband didn't exactly look with favor on the large animal.
The majority of it was some lameness and some screw worms that I picked out of a horse's hoof and scared the hell out of him.
But I did limit it.
There were horses around us.
We were in the county, just inside Lukeport County.
It was not in the city at all.
Broadway didn't even run all the way through out here.
Scrivener's was the end of the earth, wasn't it?
Not the country.
I mean, you see deer running right out here where this building is.
The country store.
Now, roughly what year is this when your clinic first opened?
See, I graduated in 47, December 47.
So I was 48, 49.
And I laughed about your poultry bit because we used to buy chicks from Casimir Cheryl Hatchery in Bryan, remember?
They had the highline chickens.
Yeah, highline chickens.
And talk about the
a brew mill over there.
We dressed 150 friars every Saturday morning and took them over to art over here at Oak Grove.
It was a brew mill and restaurant.
Those first few years, could you talk about that in your clinic as you got started?
Well, yeah, I guess I was somewhat of an oddity.
I had done some relief work for Al Nagel
and for Perry Stein and a few of the others around.
So I wasn't ostracized by any potential clients that I would call.
You didn't run into any client resistance?
No, they'd call on the phone, you know, I need to talk to Dr. Betts, and I'd say, this is she.
And over where I am now, you know, they'd call, man, hey, Dr., catch that lady on line four.
Good afternoon, may I help you?
I want to talk to the veterinarian.

well I know because you know you know when Mary when Mary Mainster started with me you know I had some clients you know we're used to me and they'd say well I don't want that one there now conversely though would you not also have attracted a certain client I think this is because in households the
the wife, the mother, is the one who takes care of the animals.
Well, of course, Mary, we used to laugh about it.
Mary would say, well, you know, she had one, and once in a while, didn't want that man in her ear.
Yeah.
So it worked out.
Yeah.
I didn't have any problem with myself.
I mean, I knew this was what I wanted, and hey, you know, that's just the brains.
Right.
Okay.
Now, our classmates used to razz me in our bacteriology props that
Oh, Nellie, don't worry.
There's always a vet school in Tuskegee for niggers and women.
But I was the one that babysat his kids.
I mean, I was the one that he called the babysat.
